    "# Naming Variables\n",
    "\n",
    "You need to follow some mandatory rules. However, it is also a good practice to give variables names that have meaning in the context of the program.\n",
    "In C# variables follow the camel-Casing naming convention, while consts use the SCREAMING_CAPS convention.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Bad Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "`double eg = 9.8;`\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Good Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "`double earthGravity = 9.8;`\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Overkill\n",
    "\n",
    "`double earth_gravity_in_meters_per_second = 9.8;`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "double eg = 9.8; # Somewhat vague \n",
    "double earthGravity = 9.8;\n",
    "double earth_gravity_in_meters_per_second = 9.8; # This is correct, but much more complicated than it needs to be"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "9.8 = 9.8 = 9.8\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(eg,\"=\",earthGravity,\"=\", earth_gravity_in_meters_per_second)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "# Variable Types\n",
    "\n",
    "There are several types of variables built into C#. The most common are byte, short, int (integers), long, float, double, decimal, complex, bool (booleans), char (characters), string (strings), and objects. Each accepts certain type and amount of data by default.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "* Byte, short, int, long, float, double, and decimal all deal with various numbers\n",
    "* Bool can only be \"True\" or \"False\"\n",
    "* String and char are used to work with text-based information\n",
    "* Const are \"immutable\" data that can not be changed\n",
    "\n",
    "## Declare and print the following examples:\n",
    "\n",
    "`int integerNumber = 5;`<br/>\n",
    "`long longNumber = 5;`<br/>\n",
    "`float floatNumber = 5.3f;`<br/>\n",
    "`double doubleNumber = 5.3;`<br/>\n",
    "`char charNumber = \'5\';`<br/>\n",
    "`string stringNumber = \"Five\";`<br/>\n",
    "`bool boolNumber = True;`<br/>\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "int integerNumber = 5\n",
    "long longNumber = 5\n",
    "float floatNumber = 5.3f;\n",
    "double doubleNumber = 5.3;\n",
    "char charNumber = \'5\';\n",
    "string stringNumber = \"Five\";\n",
    "bool boolNumber = True;\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Now try the following combinations\n",
    "\\[__Note:__ You will see some errors, we will discuss them\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "`integerNumber * floatNumber`<br/>\n",
    "`doubleNumber * floatNumber`<br/>\n",
    "`integerNumber * stringNumber`<br/>\n",
    "`floatNumber * stringNumber`<br/>\n",
    "`doubleNumber * stringNumber`<br/>\n",
    "`stringNumber + stringNumber`__<-- This is called a string \"concatenation\"__ <br/>\n",
    "`charNumber + charNumber`<br/>\n",
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Variable Type Converstion\n",
    "\n",
    "There may arise times in which you do want to \"concatenate\" a float to a string, or use a float as an integer. In those cases you can use the ToString() method to make the conversion. \\[__Note:__ A method is a group of code that is used with a single command\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "### Sample Conversion Methods:\n",
    "* `int.Parse()`<br/>\n",
    "* `float.Parse()`<br/>\n",
    "* `.ToStrings()`<br/>\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "We know `doubleNumber + stringNumber` will not concatenate because `doubleNumber` is neither a string nor an integer. But, now we know we can convert `doubleNumber` to a string by using `doubleNumber.ToString()`.   "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "doubleNumber.ToString() + stringNumber"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# What if I don't know what type of variable I am using?\n",
    "\n",
    "The `Type varType = var.GetType();` method can be used to find out. \n",
    "\n",
    "## Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "Run the code in the cell below to see what type of variable `has_car` is. \\[__Reminder:__ If you have a problem running the cell, make sure it is the correct cell type in the toolbar.\\]  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "bool hasCar = False; #Sets the default car status\n",
    "print(\"The has_car default status is\",hasCar,\"and it the variable type\",type(hasCar))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Example 2:\n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's have a little fun with the `floatNumber` variable. Guess what you think the output will be, then run the cell."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "print(floatNumber*3)\n",
    "print(str(floatNumber)*3)\n",
    "print(int(floatNumber)*3, \"<--- int(floatNumber) truncates (no rounding) 5.3 to 5 first\" ) "
   ]
